      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at our quarterly reports and shrinkage is way higher than last year. how do i actually calculate the impact this has on our inventory turnover ratio? i need the formula to show my boss how much this is messing with our efficiency.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage directly impacts your inventory turnover ratio because it means you're selling less than you think you are, or that your inventory is disappearing, which is a real drain on efficiency. You need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) upwards to reflect the true cost of the goods you *actually* sold.\n\nHere's the basic formula for Inventory Turnover Ratio: **Cost of Goods Sold / Average Inventory**.\n\nWhen you're dealing with high shrinkage, you need to make sure your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** is accurate. If shrinkage is high, you need to subtract that loss from your reported sales to get a more accurate COGS figure for that period. A smaller, more accurate COGS will make your turnover ratio look better, which is what you want to show your boss, even though the underlying reality is that your inventory is being stolen or lost.",
